		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Cincinnati</placeName> <date>Feby 13<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1834</date></p>
				<p>Dear <addressee>Isaac</addressee>&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I have postponed writing to you&#44; <sic>untill</sic> <persName>Mr Block</persName><lb/> went on&#44; but as it is now a matter of doubt whether he will<lb/> go at all&#44; I will not longer delay altho&#39; I can with difficulty<lb/> hold my pen as I have a very sore finger&#8212;indeed my dear<lb/> fellow&#44; I am very much at a loss for a subject&#44; for sentimental<lb/> letters I write more&#44; local matter would be uninteresting<lb/> &#38; Political I do not understand&#44; yet I could manage to <add>&#63;</add><lb/> your attention for a few minutes I suppose could I bring<lb/> myself once more to like letter writing&#44; but really after<lb/> having written three letters&#44; one to <persName>Aunt Leixa<add>&#63;</add></persName> <placeName>New York</placeName><lb/> to <persName>Mrs Spotswood</persName> &#38; <persName>Miss Ettings</persName>&#44; I am <sic>hartily</sic> tired of<lb/> the business&#59; however to begin something we have received<lb/> your Books&#44; and I am very much pleased with it&#44;<lb/> I am almost ashamed to confess that I did not get<lb/> through with the first copy sent as I found much<lb/> difficulty in <sic>peacing</sic> them together and the children<lb/> would bother and pull them about so that I got<lb/> impatient and awaited its arrival in a more<lb/> tangible form&#44; and I do request you not to trouble<lb/> yourself to send me <hi rend="underline">your next</hi> production <sic>untill</sic> it<lb/> is completed for it would be useless trouble&#44; as I<lb/> can read so little at the time&#44; I wish to find the peace</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>at which I last left off with the greatest case&#44; I have<lb/> mentioned you &#38; your work to <persName>Mrs Spotswood</persName>&#44; and I presume<lb/> she would like to procure a copy I should be pleased were<lb/> it to get in such able hands&#44; I do not know the number<lb/> of copies sold&#44; <persName>Mr B.</persName> will write you of them when dispo<lb/>sed of&#44; the Jews here are like they are elsewhere rather<lb/> read any thing&#44; understand any thing sooner than their<lb/> religion.  I hear <persName>Seixas Nathan</persName>&#44; is broke for a million<lb/> of Dollars&#44; is it really true&#63; <sic>let</sic> me know when you<lb/> next write all you know of the matter&#8212;what<lb/> was the <sic>occation</sic> of <persName>Miss Cohen&#39;s</persName> death do you know&#63;<lb/>  I was very much shocked to hear it&#8212;are you better<lb/> I heard you had been sick&#44; I think <persName>Isaac</persName> a<lb/> trip this way would be of service to you the sight of<lb/> old friends better than medicine suppose you try<lb/> it and let me have the pleasure of seeing you soon<lb/> I have a room at your disposal&#44; and you could<lb/> be as much retired when you wish as you <add>&#63;</add><lb/> indeed I&#39;m sure <sic>travelling</sic> over the mountains<lb/> would be of great service to you and I should be<lb/> delighted to see you at my house&#8212;your old friend<lb/> <persName>Eleanor</persName> is quite well&#44; her husband is with you before this<lb/> <persName>Mrs Marks</persName> a family are also well and desire<lb/> remembrance&#8212;Present me to all <sic>enquiring</sic> friends</p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p>I don&#39;t feel like writing any more and my<lb/> finger refuses to hold the pen any longer so<lb/> adieu your friend</p>
				<p><persName role="author">AB</persName>&#95;&#95;</p>
